{
  "lessonAim": "Identify the three primary types of earthing systems and the specific components required for Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS).",
  "taskMode": "Identification and classification of earthing arrangements and safety components.",
  "teachCheckCount": 2,
  "teachChecks": [
    {

{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "ADS",
      "simpleDefinition": "Automatic Disconnection of Supply; a safety strategy that cuts power instantly if a fault occurs to prevent electric shock.",
      "anchor": "The 'safety trip' that stops a fault from becoming fatal.",
      "misconception": "Thinking ADS is a single component; it is actually a system of parts working together."
    },
    {
      "term": "TT System",
      "simpleDefinition": "An earthing system where the consumer provides their own connection to Earth, usually via a rod driven into the ground.",
      "anchor": "Terra-Terra: Earth at the source and a rod in the garden.",
      "misconception": "Believing the supplier provides the earth in a TT system."
    },
    {
      "term": "TN-S System",
      "simpleDefinition": "An earthing system where the neutral and earth conductors are kept separate throughout the entire network from the transformer to the installation.",
      "anchor": "Terre-Neutral Separated: A separate earth path all the way back.",
      "misconception": "Confusing the cable sheath earth of a TN-S with the combined neutral/earth of a TN-C-S."
    },
    {
      "term": "TN-C-S System",
      "simpleDefinition": "An earthing system where the neutral and earth are combined in the supplier's network but separated at the consumer's intake.",
      "anchor": "Combined in the street, split at the cutout.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the earth and neutral remain combined inside the building's circuits."
    },
    {
      "term": "CPC",
      "simpleDefinition": "Circuit Protective Conductor; the specific wire within a circuit that connects metal parts to the main earthing terminal.",
      "anchor": "The green and yellow wire in your twin and earth cable.",
      "misconception": "Calling every green and yellow wire an 'earthing conductor'; the CPC is only for individual circuits."
    },
    {
      "term": "Main Protective Bonding",
      "simpleDefinition": "Cables used to connect 'extraneous' metal parts, like gas and water pipes, to the main earthing terminal.",
      "anchor": "The thick 10mm cables clamped to your metal utility pipes.",
      "misconception": "Thinking bonding is meant to carry fault current from an appliance; it is actually to keep all metalwork at the same voltage."
    },
    {
      "term": "Earthing Conductor",
      "simpleDefinition": "The main conductor that connects the installation's Main Earth Terminal to the supplier's earth or an earth electrode.",
      "anchor": "The 'master' earth wire for the whole building.",
      "misconception": "Confusing this with a CPC; the earthing conductor is the single main link to the ground/source."
    },
    {
      "term": "Protective Device",
      "simpleDefinition": "A component such as a fuse or circuit breaker (MCB) designed to break the circuit during an overcurrent or fault.",
      "anchor": "The fuse or breaker that 'pops' to stop the current.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the device only protects against fire; in ADS, it is specifically timed to prevent electric shock."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "TT uses a rod in the ground.",
    "TN-S has a separate earth path all the way.",
    "TN-C-S is combined in the street and split at the intake.",
    "ADS requires both a path (CPC) and a device (Fuse/MCB).",
    "Bonding connects the pipes; earthing connects the circuits."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "The difference between an Earthing Conductor and a CPC.",
    "The location of the neutral-earth split in a TN-C-S system.",
    "The fact that ADS is a system of components, not just a single breaker.",
    "The purpose of bonding versus the purpose of earthing."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Earthing System Types",
      "objective": "Identify and distinguish between TT, TN-S, and TN-C-S earthing systems.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the UK, we use three main earthing systems to ensure fault current has a safe path back to the supply transformer. A TN-S system (Terre-Neutral Separated) keeps the neutral and earth conductors completely separate throughout the entire network. You will see a separate earth connection, often using the cable sheath, at the intake.",
        "In a TN-C-S system (Terre-Neutral Combined-Separated), the supplier combines the neutral and earth into a single conductor in the street, but they are split into two distinct terminals at your cutout. This is the most common modern system.",
        "Finally, a TT system (Terra-Terra) is used when the supplier does not provide an earth terminal. Here, the installation relies on a local earth electrode, such as a copper rod driven into the ground, to create its own connection to Earth. Each system is defined by how the installation connects to the source of supply."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about whether the earth and neutral are separate, combined in the street, or if you have to provide your own rod in the ground."
    },
    {
      "title": "ADS Component Parts",
      "objective": "Identify the specific components required for Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS).",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS) is a coordinated system of components designed to cut power instantly during a fault. The Earthing Conductor is the 'master' cable connecting your Main Earthing Terminal (MET) to the supplier's earth or an earth electrode. From the MET, individual Circuit Protective Conductors (CPCs) run to every circuit to provide a path for fault current.",
        "We also use Main Protective Bonding—thick green and yellow cables—to connect metal gas and water pipes to the MET. This ensures all metalwork stays at the same voltage to prevent shocks. In TT systems, an earth electrode (like a rod) is a critical component to reach the mass of earth.",
        "The final part of the system is the Protective Device, such as a circuit breaker (MCB) or fuse. This device detects the high current flowing through the CPC during a fault and 'trips' or blows to disconnect the power."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember: the CPC is for individual circuits, bonding is for metal pipes, and the earthing conductor is the main link to the source."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Earthing System Types",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "In a TN-S earthing system, what does the letter 'S' stand for?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Separated",
            "Separate",
            "The conductors are kept separate"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "At what specific location in a TN-C-S system are the combined neutral and earth conductors split into two distinct terminals?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "The cutout",
            "The intake",
            "The consumer's intake",
            "The supplier's cutout"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What component must a consumer provide to connect to Earth if they are using a TT system?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Earth electrode",
            "Earth rod",
            "Copper rod",
            "A rod driven into the ground"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why is a TT system considered different from TN-S and TN-C-S regarding the path the fault current takes back to the transformer?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "It does not use a metallic conductor provided by the supplier",
        "It relies on the mass of earth to complete the circuit",
        "The return path is through the ground via an electrode",
        "The supplier does not provide an earth terminal"
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on whether the earth path is a wire provided by the supplier or a rod you put in the ground."
    },
    {
      "title": "ADS Component Parts",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What is the name of the specific conductor that runs to every individual circuit to provide a path for fault current?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Circuit Protective Conductor",
            "CPC",
            "The green and yellow wire in a circuit"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which component is used to connect extraneous metalwork, such as gas and water pipes, to the Main Earthing Terminal?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Main Protective Bonding",
            "Bonding conductors",
            "Main bonding"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the name of the single 'master' cable that connects the entire installation's Main Earthing Terminal to the source of earth?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Earthing Conductor",
            "The main earthing conductor",
            "The link between the MET and the supplier earth"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "How does the relationship between the CPC and the Protective Device (like an MCB) ensure the safety strategy of ADS works during a fault?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "The CPC provides a low-resistance path for the fault current",
        "The high current flow through the CPC is detected by the protective device",
        "The protective device trips or blows to disconnect the power",
        "They work together to stop the fault from being fatal by cutting power instantly"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about how the wire (path) allows the breaker (device) to see the fault and react."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: System Connections and Components",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between earthing system types and the specific components required to complete the ADS path.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In a TN-C-S system, the supplier provides the earth path via their own network cables by combining it with the neutral. In a TT system, the supplier provides no earth terminal at all, meaning the installer is responsible for creating a path to the mass of earth.",
      "While both systems use an Earthing Conductor to link the Main Earthing Terminal (MET) to the 'source' of earth, the physical component it connects to changes depending on the system type."
    ],
    "questionText": "Compare a TN-C-S installation to a TT installation: Describe the different termination points for the main Earthing Conductor in both systems, and name the specific component that must be installed in the ground for the TT system to function.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "In a TN-C-S system, the Earthing Conductor terminates at the supplier's intake/cut-out (the combined neutral-earth terminal).",
      "In a TT system, the Earthing Conductor terminates at an Earth Electrode.",
      "The specific component required for the TT system is the Earth Electrode (or earth rod)."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about who provides the earth connection—the electric company at the meter, or the installer using a rod in the garden."
  }
}

